          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Serial comma",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "attrs": {
            "textAlign": "left"
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Use the serial comma. It goes before “and” or “or” in a list of three or more items. It helps distinguish between the last two items.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "attrs": {
            "textAlign": "left"
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Compare these sentences:",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "bulletList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "attrs": {
                    "textAlign": "left"
                  },
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "I want to thank my parents, Juan, and Ana.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "attrs": {
                    "textAlign": "left"
                  },
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "I want to thank my parents, Juan and Ana.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "attrs": {
            "textAlign": "left"
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "In the first sentence, Juan and Ana are not the subject's parents. The first sentence contains  three parallel items, so it takes a serial comma. ",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "attrs": {
            "textAlign": "left"
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "In the second sentence, Juan and Ana are the subject's parents.  The second sentence contains a noun with an appositive, not three parallel items, so it doesn't take a serial comma.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  },
